{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013rF3umKdbSGwnh1cuuWiF9","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# authz\n2\t\n3\tPurpose: RBAC sub-package — manages roles, user-role assignments, and permission checks via an in-memory store.\n4\t\n5\tTags: api, model\n6\t\n7\t## Overview\n8\t\n9\tThe `authz` package provides a self-contained RBAC implementation. It exposes a single `Handler` that wires five HTTP routes for creating roles, assigning them to users, and evaluating whether a user holds a given permission string. All state is kept in an in-memory store guarded by a `sync.RWMutex`; there is no persistence layer.\n10\t\n11\t## File Index\n12\t\n13\t| File | Description | Doc |\n14\t|------|-------------|-----|\n15\t| `authz.go` | Role and assignment models, in-memory store, and HTTP Handler with five RBAC routes | [authz.go.md](authz.go.md) |\n16\t\n17\t## Constraints and Invariants\n18\t\n19\t- **No persistence** — all roles and assignments are lost on process restart.\n20\t- **Append-only assignments** — there is no API to revoke a role from a user once assigned.\n21\t- **nil-safe permissions** — `addRole` normalises a `nil` permissions slice to `[]string{}` so JSON responses never emit `null` for that field.\n22\t- **Role existence enforced at assignment** — `assignRole` rejects assignments that reference an unknown role ID, preventing dangling references in the assignments slice.\n23\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"65032034-364f-48b2-ba2e-5a01f1ef1498","uuid":"56b4f670-1f60-4683-9653-dd29c41b88e4","timestamp":"2026-04-05T22:30:45.625Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/david/Go/src/github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/establish-regression-recordings/sandbox/regressions/doc-platform-monolith/output/internal/iam/authz/README.md","content":"# authz\n\nPurpose: RBAC sub-package — manages roles, user-role assignments, and permission checks via an in-memory store.\n\nTags: api, model\n\n## Overview\n\nThe `authz` package provides a self-contained RBAC implementation. It exposes a single `Handler` that wires five HTTP routes for creating roles, assigning them to users, and evaluating whether a user holds a given permission string. All state is kept in an in-memory store guarded by a `sync.RWMutex`; there is no persistence layer.\n\n## File Index\n\n| File | Description | Doc |\n|------|-------------|-----|\n| `authz.go` | Role and assignment models, in-memory store, and HTTP Handler with five RBAC routes | [authz.go.md](authz.go.md) |\n\n## Constraints and Invariants\n\n- **No persistence** — all roles and assignments are lost on process restart.\n- **Append-only assignments** — there is no API to revoke a role from a user once assigned.\n- **nil-safe permissions** — `addRole` normalises a `nil` permissions slice to `[]string{}` so JSON responses never emit `null` for that field.\n- **Role existence enforced at assignment** — `assignRole` rejects assignments that reference an unknown role ID, preventing dangling references in the assignments slice.\n","numLines":23,"startLine":1,"totalLines":23}}}
